<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<Data CreatedBy="admin" CreatedOn="634303578070641013" UpdatedBy="admin" UpdatedOn="634304476577873017">
  <Properties />
  <Nodes>
    <Header Code="HeaderElement1" Type="Title" ShowInTOC="1"><![CDATA[Events handling levels]]></Header>
    <Paragraph Code="ParagraphElement1"><![CDATA[<p>The events of RibbonBar control and items could be handled on few different levels. It simplifies application logic implementation and increases flexibility.<br />These levels are:</p><ol><li>RibbonBar control events</li><li>RibbonBar control events that&nbsp;aggregates Items and SubItems event handling&nbsp;</li><li>Item and SubItem objects events</li><li>Item and SubItem underlying control events (like Button,&nbsp;CheckBox, TextBox, ComboBox)</li></ol><p>The example demonstrates all levels of events handling.</p>]]></Paragraph>
    <Header Code="HeaderElement2" Type="Title" ShowInTOC="1"><![CDATA[RibbonBar control events]]></Header>
    <Paragraph Code="ParagraphElement2"><![CDATA[<p>The RibbonBar has a lot of events common for all Visual WebGui controls.<br />It also has the unique event related to it's functionality:</p><p><em>SelectedIndexChanged</em> event&nbsp;happens when user switches the pages.&nbsp;Use this event to ensure the content presented on the page is valid and up to date. See the similar usage in the example to update status lebels and to hide and show page related content.</p>]]></Paragraph>
    <Header Code="HeaderElement3" Type="Title" ShowInTOC="1"><![CDATA[RibbonBar control aggregating events]]></Header>
    <Paragraph Code="ParagraphElement3"><![CDATA[<p>The RibbonBar control provides single place to handle events that could be raised by multiple Items and SubItems.&nbsp;Of course there is a way to know what is the object raised the event.<br />These events are:</p><ul><li><strong>AdvancedClicked</strong>, raised when advanced anchor clicked, provides&nbsp;RibbonBarGroupArgs with the the Group's anchor been clicked.</li><li><strong>ButtonClick, </strong>raised by button items when clicked, provides&nbsp;RibbonBarButtonItemArgs with the Button been clicked.</li><li><strong>CheckChanged</strong>, raised when any RibbonBarCheckBoxItem checked or unchecked, provides&nbsp;RibbonBarCheckBoxItemArgs with CheckBox been checked/unchecked.</li><li><strong>TextChanged, </strong>raised when the text of any RibbonBarTextBox SubItem changed</li></ul><p>See example's source code. The region &quot;<em>2) RibbonBar Aggregating Event Handlers</em>&quot; contains example code handling these kind of events.</p>]]></Paragraph>
    <Header Code="HeaderElement4" Type="Title" ShowInTOC="1"><![CDATA[Item and SubItem objects events]]></Header>
    <Paragraph Code="ParagraphElement4"><![CDATA[<p>The different types of Items and SubItems provides events to handle to implement applicaiton logic.</p><p>RibbonBarButtonItem and&nbsp;RibbonBarDropDownButtonItem</p><ul><li><strong>Click</strong></li><li><strong>MenuClick</strong></li></ul><p>RibbonBarComboBoxItem</p><ul><li><strong>TextChanged</strong></li></ul><p>See example's source code. The region <em>&quot;3) Item and SubItem objects events&quot;</em>&nbsp;contains example code handling these kind of events.</p>]]></Paragraph>
    <Header Code="HeaderElement5" Type="Title" ShowInTOC="1"><![CDATA[Item and SubItem underlying control events]]></Header>
    <Paragraph Code="ParagraphElement5"><![CDATA[<p>The last and most powefull level of event handling is underlying control events.&nbsp;RibbonBarItem and all derived classes has Control property that references the underlying Item's control. It different and depends on Item's type. For example the&nbsp;RibbonBarCheckBoxItem has underlying Gizmox.WebGui.Forms.CheckBox in Control property. Such way the specific properties and events available for handling.</p><p>The example's source code region <em>&quot;4) Item and SubItem underlying control events&quot;</em> contains example where&nbsp;SelectedIndexChanged event for&nbsp;RibbonBarComboBoxItem handled to provide visual hint when index changing.</p><p><strong>Pay attention:</strong>&nbsp;The implementation of Control property is subject to change. We recommend to avoid this level of event handling where it's possible and use control aggregating events and Item/SubItem events instead.</p>]]></Paragraph>
  </Nodes>
</Data>